question: How does KMN's performance on DAVIS 2017 validation compare with SWEM's performance on the same dataset when using additional training data like YouTube-VOS?
answer: KMN achieves an $\\\\textbf{82.8\\\\text{%}}$ $\\\\textbf{J\\\\text{&}F}$ score on the DAVIS 2017 validation set with YouTube-VOS, compared to SWEM's $\\\\textbf{84.3\\\\text{%}}$ score.
reference: Kernelized Memory Network for Video Object Segmentation; SWEM: Towards Real-Time Video Object Segmentation with Sequential Weighted Expectation-Maximization.

question: How does the segmentation performance of SWEM compare with KMN on the DAVIS 2016 validation set when additional YouTube-VOS training data is used?
answer: On the DAVIS 2016 validation set, KMN achieves a $\\\\textbf{90.5\\\\text{%}}$ $\\\\textbf{J\\\\text{&}F}$ score with YouTube-VOS, compared to SWEM's score of $\\\\textbf{91.3\\\\text{%}}$. Thus, SWEM shows better performance.
reference: Kernelized Memory Network for Video Object Segmentation; SWEM: Towards Real-Time Video Object Segmentation with Sequential Weighted Expectation-Maximization.

question: On the DAVIS 2016 val set, how does SWEM's performance at a higher inference speed compare to KMN when both utilize additional YouTube-VOS training data?
answer: SWEM, running at 36 FPS, achieves a $91.3\\\\%$ $\\\\mathcal{J}\\\\&\\\\mathcal{F}$ score, whereas KMN, which runs at 0.12s per frame, achieves $90.5\\\\%$. SWEM, therefore, demonstrates better performance while maintaining a higher inference speed.
reference: Kernelized Memory Network for Video Object Segmentation; SWEM: Towards Real-Time Video Object Segmentation with Sequential Weighted Expectation-Maximization.

question: What is the difference in overall score on the YouTube-VOS 2018 validation set between STM and HMMN when both use additional training data from YouTube-VOS?
answer: STM achieves an overall score of 79.4%, while HMMN achieves an overall score of 81.4% on the YouTube-VOS 2018 validation set when both use additional YouTube-VOS training data. This shows that HMMN performs better by 2% in terms of the overall score.
reference: SWEM: Towards Real-Time Video Object Segmentation with Sequential Weighted Expectation-Maximization; Kernelized Memory Network for Video Object Segmentation; Hierarchical Memory Matching Network for Video Object Segmentation.

question: In the YouTube-VOS 2018 validation set, compare the performance in the unseen category between CFBI and HMMN when both utilize additional training data.
answer: CFBI achieves a score of 75.3% on unseen categories, while HMMN achieves a score of 75.3% on the YouTube-VOS 2018 validation set, indicating they have similar performance in the unseen category.

question: What is the performance gain of SWEM over HMMN on the DAVIS 2016 validation set when both utilize additional YouTube-VOS training data?
answer: SWEM achieves a 91.3% J&F score on the DAVIS 2016 validation set with additional YouTube-VOS training, whereas HMMN achieves a 90.8% J&F score. SWEM therefore has a performance gain of 0.5%.
